# Solid-state drive

A solid-state drive (SSD) is a type of [solid-state storage](/Solid-state_storage) device that uses [integrated circuits](/Integrated_circuit) to store data [persistently](/Persistence_(computer_science)). It is sometimes called semiconductor storage device, solid-state device, or solid-state disk. &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93;

SSDs rely on non-volatile memory, typically [flash memory](/Flash_memory), to store data in [memory cell](/Memory_cell_(computing)) arrays. The performance and endurance of SSDs vary depending on the number of bits stored per cell, ranging from high‑performing single‑level cells (SLC) to more affordable but slower quad‑level cells (QLC). In addition to flash‑based SSDs, other technologies such as [3D XPoint](/3D_XPoint) offer faster speeds and higher endurance through different data storage mechanisms.

Unlike traditional [hard disk drives](/Hard_disk_drive) (HDDs), SSDs have no moving parts, allowing them to deliver faster data access speeds, reduced latency, increased resistance to physical shock, lower power consumption, and silent operation.

Often interfaced to a system in the same way as HDDs, SSDs are used in a variety of devices, including [personal computers](/Personal_computer), [enterprise servers](/Server_(computing)), and [mobile devices](/Mobile_device). However, SSDs are generally more expensive on a per‑gigabyte basis and have a finite number of write cycles, which can lead to data loss over time. Despite these limitations, SSDs are increasingly replacing HDDs, especially in performance‑critical applications and as primary storage in many consumer devices.

SSDs come in various form factors and interface types, including [SATA](/SATA), [PCIe](/PCI_Express), and [NVMe](/NVMe), each offering different levels of performance. Hybrid storage solutions, such as [solid-state hybrid drives](/Solid-state_hybrid_drive) (SSHDs), combine SSD and HDD technologies to offer improved performance at a lower cost than pure SSDs.

