## Attributes

An SSD stores data in [semiconductor](/Semiconductor) cells, with its properties varying according to the number of [bits](/Bit_(computing)) stored in each cell (between 1 and 4). Single‑level cells (SLC) store one bit of data per cell and provide higher performance and endurance. In contrast, multi‑level cells (MLC), triple‑level cells (TLC), and quad‑level cells (QLC) store more data per cell but have lower performance and endurance. SSDs using [3D XPoint](/3D_XPoint) technology, such as Intel's Optane, store data by changing electrical resistance instead of storing electrical charges in cells, which can provide faster speeds and longer data persistence compared to conventional flash memory. &#91;3&#93; SSDs based on [NAND flash](/NAND_flash) slowly leak charge when not powered, while heavily used consumer drives may start losing data typically after one to two years unpowered in storage. &#91;4&#93; SSDs have a limited lifetime number of writes, and also slow down as they reach their full storage capacity. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

SSDs also have internal parallelism that allows them to manage multiple operations simultaneously, which enhances their performance. &#91;5&#93;

Unlike HDDs and similar [electromechanical](/Electromechanical) [magnetic storage](/Magnetic_storage), SSDs do not have moving mechanical parts, which provides advantages such as resistance to physical shock, quieter operation, and faster access times. Their lower latency results in higher input/output rates (IOPS) than HDDs. &#91;6&#93;

Some SSDs are combined with traditional hard drives in hybrid configurations, such as Intel's Hystor and Apple's [Fusion Drive](/Fusion_Drive). These drives use both flash memory and spinning magnetic disks in order to improve the performance of frequently accessed data. &#91;7&#93; &#91;8&#93;

Traditional interfaces (e.g. [SATA](/SATA) and [SAS](/Serial_Attached_SCSI)) and [standard HDD form factors](/List_of_disk_drive_form_factors) allow such SSDs to be used as drop‑in replacements for HDDs in computers and other devices. Newer form factors such as [mSATA](/MSATA), [M.2](/M.2), [U.2](/U.2), [NF1](/Samsung_NF1)/[M.3](/M.3_(computing))/[NGSFF](/NGSFF), &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93; [XFM Express](/XFM_Express) ( [Crossover Flash Memory](/Crossover_Flash_Memory) , form factor XT2) &#91;11&#93; and [EDSFF](/Enterprise_and_Data_Center_Standard_Form_Factor) &#91;12&#93; &#91;13&#93; and higher speed interfaces such as [NVM Express](/NVM_Express) over [PCI Express](/PCI_Expression) (PCIe) can further increase performance over HDD performance. &#91;3&#93;

